post_text: We understand the hesitancy on the part of some parents to send their children back to school and the multitude of questions that will arise. Please know that we are doing our due diligence in coordination with the Indiana Dept. of Health, the HC Health Dept., the Governor, the Dept. of Ed, our own stakeholders and other HC school districts to create the safest, most comprehensive and reasonable plan we can. You can expect more information as soon as we have it. Watch your emails and check our social media for updates to our website coming soon.

post_text: North West Hendricks Schools are opening on time - August 5 with modifications and precautions. All Hendricks County school districts are working together and with the HC Health Dept. to make sure our students, staff, and families stay safe and healthy when we get back to our classrooms. Parents, please check your email for a message with more information from Dr. Syverson and the joint letter from the county superintendents. Information will be regularly updated here and on the website. Reopening our schools will truly require the partnership of our parents and community!

post_text:
College Board announces plans for at-home SAT

The College Board announced Wednesday a plan for at-home SAT exams -- similar to its plan for Advanced Placement exams -- if school closures continue into the fall. If by fall schools reopen, then the College Board will hold makeup exam dates for canceled spring tests and, if safe, will resume monthly SAT test dates in August through the end of the year.

post_text:
Dear Parents,

I appreciate your patience as we work through these challenging circumstances to create the best possible At Home Learning Plan for our students. We will have a plan and more detailed information available to you next week.

I realize you have many questions regarding end of year activities, grades, summer school, etc. Many of these answers will require direction from the Indiana Department of Education and we will share that information as soon as we get guidance from the IDOE.

In the meantime, we're all hoping for a warm and sunny Spring Break and we'll be “Moving Forward” with At Home Learning the week of April 13th! Stay positive and healthy!

Yours in Education,

Dr. Scott Syverson
Superintendent

post_text:
Tonight's NWHSC board meeting will be held at TWMS at 6:30 pm as it has for the past several months. It will also be available to watch from the comfort and safety of your home via Facebook Live at the NWHSC page.

We encourage you to use your best judgement in protecting your health and that of others. However, if you choose to attend the meeting, please be aware that only 50 people total will be allowed into the meeting area to comply with health officials and Governor Holcomb's directives. Once that limit is reached the doors will be locked.

Doors will open at 6:15 pm.

post_text:
A couple of FAQs have been added to our website.

Will students have to make up these missed days?
In his statement yesterday, Gov. Holcomb provided a 20-day waiver for all school districts who close school. We will only miss 9 days prior to spring break which means we will not need to make up those days. IF our schools need to remain closed for a longer period of time after spring break, we have 11 instructional days that could still be waived.

Many schools are utilizing e-learning to compensate for missed instructional days. Why isn't NWHSC?
NWHSC is not a one-to-one computing district and we have places throughout the district with no internet service, so we are not equipped to provide E-Learning at this time. E-Learning is, however, something we are currently looking into.
text:

Many schools are utilizing e-learning to compensate for missed instructional days. Why isn't NWHSC?
NWHSC is not a one-to-one computing district and we have places throughout the district with no internet service, so we are not equipped to provide E-Learning at this time. E-Learning is, however, something we are currently looking into.

NWHSC and the school board appreciate the comments, questions and concerns expressed by our community members over the past few months. We acknowledge that there has been too little information forthcoming and that has caused misinformation, speculation and mistrust to flourish.

We are committed to providing greater transparency and communication in the future, starting with an FAQ you can access from a tab at the top of the website. This forum will respond to questions pertaining to North West Hendricks School Corp. It will remain a dynamic public document on the district webpage, so that information is consistent and available for reference and resource.

If you have questions, please send them to: questions@hendricks.k12.in.us

post_text:
You may have seen recent information regarding a recall of some Thomas school buses. NWHSC does have Thomas buses in its fleet and we are awaiting word on which ones are affected. We want to assure you that ALL our buses are safe and share a memo we received earlier today from the Indiana State Police regarding the safety of the buses and their recall status:

"The affected buses are still safe to use. Kerlin Bus Sales will contact the owners of the affected buses directly once they have established a repair procedure," Sgt. Chris Kath, School Bus Safety Coordinator/Quarter Master/Data Q's, Indiana State Police.

Once we have received notification we will proceed with those repairs as soon as possible.
